[{"location":"api/#API-Reference","page":"API Reference","title":"API Reference","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"api/#Dimensionless-numbers","page":"API Reference","title":"Dimensionless numbers","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"api/#Frequencies","page":"API Reference","title":"Frequencies","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"api/#Lengths","page":"API Reference","title":"Lengths","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"api/#Velocites","page":"API Reference","title":"Velocites","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"api/#Speeds","page":"API Reference","title":"Speeds","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"api/#Current-density","page":"API Reference","title":"Current density","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"api/#Aliases","page":"API Reference","title":"Aliases","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"api/#Constants","page":"API Reference","title":"Constants","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"api/#Otherwise-undocumented-functions","page":"API Reference","title":"Otherwise undocumented functions","text":"This section will be removed once the documentation is complete.","category":"section"},{"location":"api/#PlasmaFormulary.plasma_beta","page":"API Reference","title":"PlasmaFormulary.plasma_beta","text":"plasma_beta(T, n, B)\n\nCompute the plamsa beta (Î²), the ratio of thermal pressure to magnetic pressure.\n\nArguments\n\nT: The temperature of the plasma.\nn: The particle density of the plasma.\nB: The magnetic field in the plasma.\n\nExample\n\njulia> plasma_beta(1e6u\"K\", 1e19u\"m^-3\", 0.2u\"T\")\n0.008674873511172188\n\nReferences\n\nPlasmaPy Documentation\nWikipedia\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"function"},{"location":"api/#PlasmaFormulary.plasma_frequency","page":"API Reference","title":"PlasmaFormulary.plasma_frequency","text":"plasma_frequency(n::NumberDensity, [q::Charge, mass::Mass]; to_hz = false)\nplasma_frequency(n::NumberDensity, p::ParticleLike; kw...)\n\nCalculate the plasma frequency of a species.\n\nÏ‰_p = sqrtfracn q^2m Îµâ‚€\n\nThe plasma frequency is a characteristic frequency of the plasma.  More often, it refers to the frequency at which electrons oscillate in the plasma.\n\nSet to_hz = true to convert output from angular frequency to Hz.\n\nExamples\n\njulia> plasma_frequency(1e19u\"m^-3\")  # plasma frequency\n1.7839863654934653e11 rad sâ»Â¹\n\njulia> plasma_frequency(1e19u\"m^-3\", :p)  # proton plasma frequency\n4.1632945624883513e9 rad sâ»Â¹\n\nReferences\n\nWikipedia\nPlasmaPy Documentation\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"function"},{"location":"api/#PlasmaFormulary.gyrofrequency","page":"API Reference","title":"PlasmaFormulary.gyrofrequency","text":"gyrofrequency(B::BField, p::ParticleLike; kw...)\ngyrofrequency(B::BField, mass::Mass, q::Charge; to_hz = false)\n\nCalculate the gyrofrequency (or cyclotron frequency) of a charged particle's circular motion in a magnetic field. The gyrofrequency is the angular frequency of a charged particle's gyromotion around magnetic field lines.\n\nSet to_hz = true to convert output from angular frequency to Hz.\n\nReferences: \n\nPlasmaPy Documentation\n\nExamples\n\njulia> gyrofrequency(0.01u\"T\", :p)  # proton gyrofrequency\n957883.3292211705 rad sâ»Â¹\n\njulia> gyrofrequency(0.1u\"T\", :e; to_hz = true)  # electron gyrofrequency as frequency\n2.799248987233304e9 Hz\n\njulia> gyrofrequency(250u\"Gauss\", \"Fe\"; z=13)  # Fe2+ ion gyrofrequency\n560682.3520611608 rad sâ»Â¹\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"function"},{"location":"api/#PlasmaFormulary.gyroradius","page":"API Reference","title":"PlasmaFormulary.gyroradius","text":"Calculate the radius of circular motion for a charged particle in a uniform magnetic field\n\nReferences: PlasmaPy API Documentation\n\nExamples\n\njulia> gyroradius(0.2u\"T\", Unitful.me, Unitful.q, 1e6u\"K\")\n0.00015651672339994665 m\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"function"},{"location":"api/#PlasmaFormulary.inertial_length","page":"API Reference","title":"PlasmaFormulary.inertial_length","text":"inertial_length(n::NumberDensity, q::Charge, mass::Mass)\ninertial_length(n::NumberDensity, p::ParticleLike; kw...)\n\nCalculate the inertial length, the characteristic length scale for a particle to be accelerated in a plasma:\n\ndáµ¢ = fraccÏ‰_p\n\nwhere Ï‰_p is the plasma frequency.\n\nThe Hall effect becomes important on length scales shorter than the ion inertial length.\n\nSee also: plasma_frequency.\n\nReferences: PlasmaPy API Documentation\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"function"},{"location":"api/#PlasmaFormulary.Debye_length","page":"API Reference","title":"PlasmaFormulary.Debye_length","text":"Debye_length(n::NumberDensity, T::EnergyOrTemp)\n\nCalculate the Debye length, exponential scale length for charge screening in an electron plasma with stationary ions:\n\nÎ»_D = sqrtfracÎµâ‚€ k_B Tn q^2\n\nwhere T is the electron temperature, n is the electron density, and q is the elementary charge.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"function"},{"location":"api/#PlasmaFormulary.Alfven_velocity","page":"API Reference","title":"PlasmaFormulary.Alfven_velocity","text":"Alfven_velocity(B::BField, Ï)\nAlfven_velocity(ğ::Vector{BField}, Ï)\n\nCalculate the Alfven velocity for magnetic field vector. See also Alfven_speed.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"function"},{"location":"api/#PlasmaFormulary.diamagnetic_drift","page":"API Reference","title":"PlasmaFormulary.diamagnetic_drift","text":"diamagnetic_drift(âˆ‡p, B::BFields, n, q)\n\nCalculate the diamagnetic drift velocity given by:\n\nğ¯ = - (p  ğ)  (q n ğ^2)\n\nwhere p is the pressure gradient.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"function"},{"location":"api/#PlasmaFormulary.ExB_drift","page":"API Reference","title":"PlasmaFormulary.ExB_drift","text":"ExB_drift(ğ„::EFields, ğ::BFields)\n\nCalculate the E  ğ drift velocity given by:\n\nğ¯ = (ğ„  ğ)  ğ^2\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"function"},{"location":"api/#PlasmaFormulary.force_drift","page":"API Reference","title":"PlasmaFormulary.force_drift","text":"force_drift(ğ…, ğ::BFields, q)\n\nCalculate the general force drift for a particle in a magnetic field given by:\n\nğ¯ = (ğ…  ğ)  (q ğ^2)\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"function"},{"location":"api/#PlasmaFormulary.Alfven_speed","page":"API Reference","title":"PlasmaFormulary.Alfven_speed","text":"Alfven_speed(B::BFieldOrBFields, Ï)\nAlfven_speed(B::BFieldOrBFields, n::NumberDensity, mass_number = 1)\n\nAlfvÃ©n speed V_A, the typical propagation speed of magnetic disturbances in a quasineutral plasma.\n\nNote that this is different from the Alfven velocity, see also Alfven_velocity. References: PlasmaPy API Documentation\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"function"},{"location":"api/#PlasmaFormulary.ion_sound_speed","page":"API Reference","title":"PlasmaFormulary.ion_sound_speed","text":"ion_sound_speed(T_e, T_i, m_i, Z; Î³_e=1, Î³_i=3, n_e=nothing, k=nothing)\n\nCalculate the ion sound speed for an electron-ion plasma given by:\n\nV_S = sqrtfracÎ³_e Z k_B T_e + Î³_i k_B T_im_i (1 + k^2 Î»_D^2)\n\nIf both n_e and k are given, includes dispersive correction.\n\nArguments\n\nT_e: Electron temperature (K or energy per particle)\nT_i: Ion temperature (K or energy per particle)\nm_i: Ion mass\nZ: Ion charge state (default: 1)\nÎ³_e: Electron adiabatic index (default: 1)\nÎ³_i: Ion adiabatic index (default: 3)\nn_e: Electron number density (optional)\nk: Wavenumber (optional)\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"function"},{"location":"api/#PlasmaFormulary.thermal_speed","page":"API Reference","title":"PlasmaFormulary.thermal_speed","text":"thermal_speed(T::EnergyOrTemp, mass::Mass, method::ThermalVelocityMethod = MostProbable(), ndim = 3)\n\nCalculate the speed of thermal motion for particles with a Maxwellian distribution.\n\nv_th = C_o sqrtfrack_B Tm\n\nwhere T is the temperature associated with the distribution, m is the particle's mass, and C_o is a constant of proportionality. ```\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"function"},{"location":"api/#PlasmaFormulary.thermal_temperature","page":"API Reference","title":"PlasmaFormulary.thermal_temperature","text":"thermal_temperature(V::Velocity, mass::Mass, method::ThermalVelocityMethod = MostProbable(), ndim = 3)\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"function"},{"location":"api/#PlasmaFormulary.Alfven_current_density","page":"API Reference","title":"PlasmaFormulary.Alfven_current_density","text":"Alfven_current_density(Va::Velocity, n::NumberDensity)\nAlfven_current_density(B::BFieldOrBFields, n::NumberDensity)\nAlfven_current_density(B::BFieldOrBFields, dáµ¢::Length)\n\nCalculate the AlfvÃ©n current density J_A, a natural scaling for current density: \n\nJ_A = e n V_A = fracBÎ¼â‚€ dáµ¢\n\nwhere V_A is the Alfven speed, dáµ¢ is ion inertial length.\n\nSee also: Alfven_speed, inertial_length.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"function"},{"location":"api/#PlasmaFormulary.Aliases","page":"API Reference","title":"PlasmaFormulary.Aliases","text":"This module provides aliases of the most common plasma functionality for user convenience. \n\nAliases are denoted with a trailing underscore (e.g., alias_).\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"module"},{"location":"api/#PlasmaFormulary.thermal_velocity_coefficients","page":"API Reference","title":"PlasmaFormulary.thermal_velocity_coefficients","text":"thermal_velocity_coefficients(method::ThermalVelocityMethod, ndim::Int)\n\nGet the thermal speed coefficient corresponding to the desired thermal speed definition.\n\nArguments\n\nmethod::ThermalVelocityMethod: Method to be used for calculating the thermal speed. Valid values are MostProbable(), RMS(), MeanMagnitude(), and NRL().\nndim::Val{Int}: Dimensionality (1D, 2D, 3D) of space in which to calculate thermal speed. Valid values are Val(1), Val(2), or Val{3}.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"function"},{"location":"api/#PlasmaFormulary.magnetic_pressure-Tuple{Union{Unitful.Quantity{T, ğŒ ğˆ^-1 ğ“^-2, U}, Unitful.Level{L, S, Unitful.Quantity{T, ğŒ ğˆ^-1 ğ“^-2, U}} where {L, S}} where {T, U}}","page":"API Reference","title":"PlasmaFormulary.magnetic_pressure","text":"magnetic_pressure(B)\n\nCalculate the magnetic pressure.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"method"},{"location":"api/#PlasmaFormulary.thermal_pressure-Tuple{Union{Unitful.Level{L, S, Unitful.Quantity{T, ğš¯, U}} where {T, U, L, S}, Unitful.Level{L, S, Unitful.Quantity{T, ğ‹^2 ğŒ ğ“^-2, U}} where {T, U, L, S}, Unitful.Quantity{T, ğš¯} where T, Unitful.Quantity{T, ğ‹^2 ğŒ ğ“^-2} where T}, Union{Unitful.Quantity{T, ğ‹^-3, U}, Unitful.Level{L, S, Unitful.Quantity{T, ğ‹^-3, U}} where {L, S}} where {T, U}}","page":"API Reference","title":"PlasmaFormulary.thermal_pressure","text":"thermal_pressure(T, n)\n\nCalculate the thermal pressure for a Maxwellian distribution.\n\nArguments\n\nT: The particle temperature or energy.\nn: The particle number density.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"method"},{"location":"#PlasmaFormulary","page":"Home","title":"PlasmaFormulary","text":"A Julia package for plasma physics formulas. This package implements a subset of the formulas found in the NRL Plasma Formulary, as well as some additional formulas taken from the PlasmaPy project.","category":"section"},{"location":"#Features","page":"Home","title":"Features","text":"For functions that take a ParticleLike as an argument, we use ChargedParticles.jl package to handle particle properties. One could provide a symbolic particle name or string or a Particle object for the argument. In addition, mass number and charge number can be specified as keyword arguments for these functions.\nFor function whose arguments are Unitful quantities with unique dimensions, arguments are order independent (see PermuteArgs.jl).","category":"section"},{"location":"#Quick-Example","page":"Home","title":"Quick Example","text":"using PlasmaFormulary, Unitful\n\ndebye_length(1e18u\"cm^-3\", 10u\"eV\")\n\ngyrofrequency(0.01u\"T\", :e) # electron gyrofrequency\n\nplasma_frequency(1e19u\"m^-3\", \"proton\") # proton plasma frequency","category":"section"},{"location":"#Installation","page":"Home","title":"Installation","text":"using Pkg\nPkg.add(\"PlasmaFormulary\")","category":"section"},{"location":"#Related-packages","page":"Home","title":"Related packages","text":"PlasmaPy : plasmapy.formulary subpackage provides theoretical formulas for calculation of physical quantities helpful for plasma physics.\nFusionFormulary.jl","category":"section"},{"location":"#Index","page":"Home","title":"Index","text":"","category":"section"}]
